-- South African Stocks Fall For Second Day, Led by MTN, Nedbank and Northam
-- B y   M i k e   C o h e n   a n d   N i c k y   S m i t h
-- 2010-10-15T15:40:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-15/equities-in-south-africa-decline-for-second-day-nedbank-old-mutual-move.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  fell for a second day, declining 185.35, or 0.6
percent, to 30,065.99 at the close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  MTN Group Ltd.  (MTN SJ), Africa’s largest mobile-phone
company, retreated 1.85 rand, or 1.4 percent, to 127, snapping
two days of gains.  Telkom South Africa Ltd.  said it would begin
mobile services on Oct. 18, offering lower prices for some calls
and text-message incentives.  Vodacom Group Ltd.  (VOD SJ), the
biggest provider of mobile-phone services to South Africans,
fell 1.10 rand, or 1.6 percent, to 67.30 rand.  Nedbank Group Ltd.  (NED SJ), South Africa’s fourth-biggest
lender, fell 9 rand, or 6.1 percent, to 137.80 rand, the biggest
drop since March 2009. HSBC Holdings Plc, Europe’s largest bank,
abandoned a bid to buy a $7.3 billion controlling stake in South
Africa’s, including a 52 percent stake owned by  Old Mutual Plc 
(OML SJ). Old Mutual declined 74 cents, or 4.7 percent, to 15.10
rand, the biggest slump since May.  Standard Bank Group Ltd.  (SBK
SJ), Africa’s largest bank, lost 1.29 rand, or 1.2 percent, to
109.20 rand.   Northam Platinum Ltd.  (NHM SJ) slipped 38 cents, or 0.8
percent, to 46.51 rand. Workers at the platinum producer’s only
mine, Zondereinde, may decide on the company’s latest wage
offer. The mine has been shut since Sept. 5 when the workers
started a strike over pay.  To contact the reporters on this story:
